headline: Subdued decision in Google antitrust trial may help keep a monopoly in power
summary: After a five-year legal showdown pitting the U.S. Department of Justice against Google, a federal judge concluded that the disruptive forces of artificial intelligence technology will have a better chance of hobbling an illegal monopoly than any restraints imposed by a court order.  After ruling that Google's dominant search engine had turned into an illegal monopoly back in August 2024, the judge spent the next 13 months mulling the best way to rein in the technology powerhouse's bad behavior.

headline: Google's AI rivals get a boost from data-sharing order, but tech giant far from routed
summary: SAN FRANCISCO (Reuters) -A rising group of artificial intelligence companies stand to gain from an antitrust ruling on Tuesday that ordered Alphabet's Google to share its invaluable search data with competitors.  Matching Google's heft, though, will take time and huge resources, with no guarantees that any rival product will win as many users, experts said.  While Google was spared the devastating outcome of having to sell its popular Chrome browser and Android operating system, U.S. District Judge Amit Mehta's ruling was a nod to regulators' efforts to level the playing field for companies who have invested billions to boost their AI business.

headline: Google won't have to sell Chrome, but must share data: judge
summary: STORY: Google will not have to sell its Chrome browser, but will have to share data with rivals to boost competition in online search.That was the ruling by a judge in Washington on Tuesday (September 2).The verdict marked a rare win for Big Tech over U.S. antitrust watchdogs.It sent shares in parent firm Alphabet soaring over 7% in extended trade.Judge Amit Mehta also ruled that Google could keep its Android operating system which, together with Chrome, helps drive its market-dominating online ads business.Mehta had ruled last year that the tech giant operated an illegal monopoly in search and related advertising.But he said he approached the task of setting remedies with “humility”.He cited the rise of AI-driven rivals as one mitigating factor.Google now faces competition from search tools powered by the likes of OpenAI’s ChatGPT.Such products could be further boosted by access to its vast troves of data.Google has said it will appeal, meaning it could take years before it is required to act on Tuesday’s ruling.U.S. regulators say they are now considering their next steps.The case is widely expected to end up in the Supreme Court.Mehta also ruled that Apple and other device and browser makers can maintain revenue sharing agreements with Google.Analysts at Morgan Stanley estimate Google pays the iPhone maker $20 billion a year for searches done on its devices.
